subtitle: British Catholics face discrimination from the <span style="color: #e67038;">**Orange**</span><span style="color: #070863;">**men**</span>\...\
choose-if: rcra_support = 1 and church_separation = 0
unavailable subtitle: [? if not rcra_support: This is not party policy. ?] [? if church_separation: Constitutional scholars in the party argue this would contradict our reforms to it. ?]

The Roman Catholic Relief Bill was first introduced in 1926 by the <span class="tooltip-text" title="Coalition National Liberal Party" style="color: #ffd600;">**CNLP**</span>, and seeks to write into law a removal of all remaining social barriers that British Catholics face, building on the Constitution's recognition of religious equality.

More religious voices in the <span class="tooltip-text" title="Coalition Conservative Party" style="color: #1375d6;">**CCP**</span> opposed it, arguing it was not necessary, and the <span class="tooltip-text" title="Coalition National Liberal Party" style="color: #ffd600;">**CNLP**</span> subsequently withdrew from government.

Now, we may choose to attempt to make the Bill law.

- @decision_time_rcra
- @religion_menu: Let's look at something else...

@decision_time_rcra 
title: We must pass the RCRA!
choose-if: rcra_coalition > anti_rcra_coalition
unavailable subtitle: We do not have the votes.
on-arrival: other_workers_lab += 1; unemployed_lab += 1; white_collar_lab -= 2; upper_lab -= 5; farmers_lab += 1; urban_workers_cup += 1; pragmatist_dissent += 5; left_dissent += 5; reformist_dissent -= 5; labour_dissent += 5; marxist_dissent += 5; reformist_strength += 5; cnlp_relation += 5; lib_relation += 2;

This is a continued break from orthodoxy which favoured non-involvement in religious affairs, and is met with displeasure from certain factions. However, we had promised this in our election campaign and are now able to deliver it!

The <span class="tooltip-text" title="Conservative & Unionist Party" style="color: #002c6e;">**CUP**</span>, naturally, campaigns against the new RCRA. We will have to see how it will be implemented in the staunchly Anti-Catholic Ulster.

